If this is longer than the duration of the experience you want to investigate, then use mrcrop to crop out the unwanted calls that have no bearing upon your analysis. If your trace file time scope is correct, then you can think of this report as an invoice explaining how your time was spent, with call counts and durations acting as quantities and prices. It will help you answer the four most important questions about an application’s performance:

  • How long did this end-user experience take?
  • Why did it consume the time that it did?
  • What if you change something? How would a proposed change impact the duration of this experience?
  • What else could you do to reduce the duration of this experience? Is the program efficient?

The advisory paragraphs that accompany the data in this document are meant to enhance your interpretation of the data. In cases where they run afoul of sound judgment, please open a case with Method R Support .

1.1. Profile by Subroutine

Your experience duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for between calls” consumed 99.8% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls”. Large call durations imply a problem with how your trace file was collected. If your trace file contains data for more than one experience, then use mrcrop to slice your trace file into smaller files, each representing a single individual experience.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for between calls” call when there is missing time between dep = 0 database and system calls. Every adjacent pair of such calls will define some non-zero “unaccounted-for between calls” duration; however, the amount per call pair should be minuscule. Large amounts per call pair occur in strange cases, such as when a program’s trace was disabled for part of its execution. You can diagnose where in your input the large durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.1.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement bgthktgrvhq40 touched the database buffer cache 20 times but processed only one row. The statement is efficient only if it joins two or more base tables, or if it is an aggregation.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed three “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least 0.002382 seconds.
  • It should be possible to return many rows per “FETCH” call, but this application returns an average of only 0.25 rows per “FETCH” call.

The statement obtained zero Oracle blocks from OS read calls, which means that your kernel process found the block it needed in the database buffer cache on 100.0% of LIOs.

Your statement duration was dominated by one type of database call:

  • “between dbcalls” calls consumed 100.0% of the statement duration. These calls should never dominate an experience duration. To reduce the call count, eliminate unnecessary database calls. To reduce the duration, check your network latencies and investigate the code path that your application executes between its Oracle database calls.

4.3.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement 23wm3kz7rps5y touched the database buffer cache two times but processed no rows, an average of 0.33 LIOs per “between dbcalls” call. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed two “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least −0.000005 seconds.

4.9.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement PROF000000083 duration was dominated by “uncategorizable within synthetic dbcalls” calls:

  • “uncategorizable within synthetic dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “uncategorizable within synthetic dbcalls”. There was probably an error in how this trace file was collected. You may be able to fix your problem with mrcrop. If not, then you will need to generate a new trace file.

    Sometimes, an Oracle Database kernel process writes trace data in which a sequence of one or more dep = n + 1 database calls or system calls will not have a following dep = n parent. This can occur, for example, (i) at the end of a trace file, when tracing is deactivated during the execution of a dep = n + 1 call for some n ≥ 0; or (ii) when mrprof expects a parent database call, but finds a dep = 0 system call instead; or (iii) in response to an Oracle Database bug. When mrprof finds such a sequence of un-parented calls, it will synthesize a database call to act as the parent for the sequence. Although mrprof can unambiguously determine that such a parent call did in fact occur, it cannot determine the call’s name, exact duration, or proportion of CPU duration to “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration. For each such event, mrprof will synthesize an “uncategorizable within synthetic dbcalls” call.

4.10.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9m5079f47zw24 duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 73.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 25.9% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.11.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9bvdr0ur4nfy2 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 90.6% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. 4.12.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 69wn4waatcmgy duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 75.5% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 22.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.14.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement c8h20n1d0k95m duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for between calls” consumed 97.3% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls”. Large call durations imply a problem with how your trace file was collected. If your trace file contains data for more than one experience, then use mrcrop to slice your trace file into smaller files, each representing a single individual experience.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for between calls” call when there is missing time between dep = 0 database and system calls. Every adjacent pair of such calls will define some non-zero “unaccounted-for between calls” duration; however, the amount per call pair should be minuscule. Large amounts per call pair occur in strange cases, such as when a program’s trace was disabled for part of its execution. You can diagnose where in your input the large durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.15.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement arxwfzs160xzf duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 51.0% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 37.6% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.15.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement arxwfzs160xzf touched the database buffer cache 35 times and processed three rows, an average of 11.67 LIOs per row. The statement is efficient only if it joins two or more base tables, or if it is an aggregation.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to process many rows per “EXEC” call, but this application processes an average of only 1.00 row per “EXEC” call.

4.17.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 50kvjc2sgknx6 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls”, “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”, and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 84.9% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 37.5% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −22.4% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −194.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.24.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement dmh17scdhqz3z duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 88.2% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

4.25.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement a1pawjmqtc793 duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.27.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement auhy7gptp3g2d duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 60.9% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 22.9% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.30.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 35ra2cdwvqg1w duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 54.2% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 44.2% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −30.3% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 20.8% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.38.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 8nhg2pdrzs3ww duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 53.0% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 34.3% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

Statement cn6hhn36a4rrs duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 66.6% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 29.5% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.41.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 2qn8u7pmquaab duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 75.2% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

Statement 0yn07bvqs30qj touched the database buffer cache 54 times and processed 18 rows, an average of 3.00 LIOs per row. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. 4.44.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 264mazaqpzmf9 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 64.3% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 54.8% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.46.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement d7zvk9bn8dyr6 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 163.2% of your experience duration. A faulty Oracle Database time measurement has caused the sum of your “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” durations to exceed your total experience duration. Though it is easy to cause this situation with trace files having just one or two lines in them, the phenomenon should be rare in real-world trace files. If you encounter this situation frequently with non-trivial trace files, log a case with Method R Support.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −63.6% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.49.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement dbvj6jc977hqh duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 138.1% of your experience duration. A faulty Oracle Database time measurement has caused the sum of your “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” durations to exceed your total experience duration. Though it is easy to cause this situation with trace files having just one or two lines in them, the phenomenon should be rare in real-world trace files. If you encounter this situation frequently with non-trivial trace files, log a case with Method R Support.
  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −38.1% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.51.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9ky1f9mda8g5v duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 50.3% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 29.9% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

If your trace file contains data for more than one experience, then use mrcrop to slice your trace file into smaller files, each representing a single individual experience.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for between calls” call when there is missing time between dep = 0 database and system calls. Large amounts per call pair occur in strange cases, such as when a program’s trace was disabled for part of its execution. 4.55.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement ftj9uawt4wwzb duration was dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” and “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 59.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 41.1% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

4.55.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement ftj9uawt4wwzb touched the database buffer cache 14 times and processed seven rows, an average of 2.00 LIOs per row. The statement used the buffer cache efficiently.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed seven “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least −0.000542 seconds.
  • It should be possible to return many rows per “FETCH” call, but this application returns an average of only 1.00 row per “FETCH” call.

The statement obtained zero Oracle blocks from OS read calls, which means that your kernel process found the block it needed in the database buffer cache on 100.0% of LIOs.

4.57.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9rzjf5cqv4qv1 duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.58.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 7m1ng2nujns5y duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 85.8% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 21.8% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.60.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement amrg3r9jw7uq5 duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 39.6% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 227.4% of your experience duration. A faulty Oracle Database time measurement has caused the sum of your “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” durations to exceed your total experience duration. Though it is easy to cause this situation with trace files having just one or two lines in them, the phenomenon should be rare in real-world trace files. If you encounter this situation frequently with non-trivial trace files, log a case with Method R Support.
  • “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” consumed 40.7% of your experience duration. “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed −172.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.62.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement 4cv3nc10n5rw0 touched the database buffer cache 12 times but processed no rows, an average of 6.00 LIOs per “EXEC” call. The statement is efficient only if it joins two or more base tables, or if it is an aggregation.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed two “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least 0.000023 seconds.
  • It should be possible to return many rows per “FETCH” call, but this application returns an average of only 0.00 rows per “FETCH” call.

The statement obtained zero Oracle blocks from OS read calls, which means that your kernel process found the block it needed in the database buffer cache on 100.0% of LIOs.

4.64.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement grfx7r30auhvj duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” and “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 62.4% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 22.1% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

4.64.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement grfx7r30auhvj touched the database buffer cache 12 times but processed no rows, an average of 2.00 LIOs per “EXEC” call. The statement is efficient only if it joins two or more base tables, or if it is an aggregation.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed six “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least 0.000157 seconds.

4.68.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 6h3cwmunz5z8q duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” and “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 72.4% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 22.8% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

A faulty Oracle Database time measurement has caused the sum of your “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” durations to exceed your total experience duration. Though it is easy to cause this situation with trace files having just one or two lines in them, the phenomenon should be rare in real-world trace files. If you encounter this situation frequently with non-trivial trace files, log a case with Method R Support.
  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 57.3% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” consumed 21.0% of your experience duration. “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. Negative-duration “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” events happen when the measured duration of a database call is smaller than the sum of the measured durations of its children. This occurs frequently as a normal consequence of the ±10,000-microsecond precision of the CPU clock, but in normal trace files with many lines, the negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls are compensated by positive values. Accumulation of large negative amounts of “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” time can be the result of, for example, a trace file collection error, a VKTM time drift, or an Oracle Database bug.

4.72.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement a4n4ayr88dbhy duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” and “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 71.2% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 25.7% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

4.74.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 07pcqtmt58zv9 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” and “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 44.5% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” consumed 36.5% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” calls. You should be able to improve response time by eliminating calls or reducing call durations.

4.75.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement gsfnqdfcvy33q duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

4.75.4. Profile by Database Call

Statement gsfnqdfcvy33q had no LIOs recorded in its trace file.

To have excellent performance and scalability, it is vital to eliminate unnecessary database calls. Each database call of course incurs the CPU cost of executing the call, but additionally, each call executed by a client program increases your network I/O call count and the unaccounted-for time your application spends both within and between calls. Opportunities to eliminate database calls include:

  • It should be possible to accomplish everything this statement does with just one “PARSE” call, but the application has executed two “PARSE” calls for this statement. Eliminating unnecessary “PARSE” calls should improve the total experience duration by at least 0.000057 seconds.
  • It should be possible to process many rows per “EXEC” call, but this application processes an average of only 0.00 rows per “EXEC” call.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.78.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 95nx0kvvb2r8m duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” consumed 100.0% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for within dbcalls”. This call type generally implies a CPU starvation problem. Call durations are usually dominated by OS preemptions. Check your CPU utilization and your paging and swapping rates. If you do find corroborating evidence of CPU starvation, then either optimize, reschedule, relocate, or eliminate your program or its competition.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” call to account for each dbcall’s under- or over-attribution of time. Almost every database call will contain some positive or negative “unaccounted-for within dbcalls” duration; however, the amount should be minuscule, and the sum of these durations over many calls should converge to zero. You can diagnose where in your input the large individual durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.
