4.79.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 3pzwf21p9utb0 duration was dominated by “CPU: EXEC dbcalls”, “CPU: FETCH dbcalls”, and “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 54.0% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” consumed 22.1% of your experience duration. “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: FETCH dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 21.2% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

4.81.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement 9nwgayayppcxj duration was dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” and “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” calls:

  • “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” consumed 57.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: PARSE dbcalls”. Long-duration “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls may require optimizer trace (event 10053) analysis. Reducing the number of “CPU: PARSE dbcalls” calls usually requires an application code change. Do not parse inside a loop that generates SQL dynamically. Instead, use placeholders in your SQL text to create a loop-invariant shareable cursor that can be reused within your loop for different bound values. See The Method R Guide to Mastering Oracle Trace Data, 3rd edition chapter 2 “Making Friends with the Oracle Database,” chapter 18 “SQL Sharing”, and chapter 19 “Unaccounted-for Time” for more information.

    An application that parses too often cannot scale to large user counts, no matter how many CPUs your system has or how fast they are, because parsing is a software-serialized operation. A good application never parses a given statement more than once per session. A great application never parses a given statement more than once per Oracle instance startup.

  • “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” consumed 29.5% of your experience duration. “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” are high-productivity calls that you do want dominating your duration. However, you do not want your application doing any more “CPU: EXEC dbcalls” work than necessary. When you are investigating a time-consuming statement, don’t be afraid to ask whether the statement is really necessary—sometimes an entire statement can be eliminated with no loss of functionality to the business. Investigate whether you can reduce your call count by using array processing, and whether each call can be made more efficient by eliminating unnecessary LIOs.

    LIO count is one good measure of a SQL statement’s efficiency. An LIO is simply an access of a buffer in the database buffer cache. But an LIO is much more than just a memory access. It is a latch-serialized operation that consumes CPU. By reducing a statement’s LIO count, you reduce not just the number of memory accesses your code executes, but you also reduce the number of CPU cycles your Oracle session consumes, the number of blocks it reads from disk or other secondary storage, the number of latches it has to acquire, the number of global cache coherency instructions it has to execute, and more.

4.82.3. Profile by Subroutine

Statement PROF000000082 duration was dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls” and “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” calls:

  • “unaccounted-for between calls” consumed 72.7% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “unaccounted-for between calls”. Large call durations imply a problem with how your trace file was collected. If your trace file contains data for more than one experience, then use mrcrop to slice your trace file into smaller files, each representing a single individual experience.

    mrprof synthesizes an “unaccounted-for between calls” call when there is missing time between dep = 0 database and system calls. Every adjacent pair of such calls will define some non-zero “unaccounted-for between calls” duration; however, the amount per call pair should be minuscule. Large amounts per call pair occur in strange cases, such as when a program’s trace was disabled for part of its execution. You can diagnose where in your input the large durations occur by using mrprof --trace=ut.

  • “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” consumed 27.3% of your experience duration. Your duration should never be dominated by “CPU: CLOSE dbcalls” calls. You should be able to improve response time by eliminating calls or reducing call durations.
